01:46.400 --> 01:48.790
Well, he's your father, Jessica.

01:49.000 --> 01:51.560
Where is he?
Well, Chester,
I... I... I don't...

01:51.760 --> 01:53.479
Benson. Benson.

01:54.840 --> 01:56.115
Benson, where is he?

01:56.320 --> 01:59.392
Wonderful.
Just wonderful.

01:59.600 --> 02:02.991
I kill myself in the kitchen
all day and then nobody eats.

02:03.200 --> 02:04.759
Benson.
Look at this.

02:04.960 --> 02:06.758
Not one plate touched.

02:06.960 --> 02:11.512
Well, let's not waste
all this good food.
Let's invite the Campbells over.

02:11.720 --> 02:14.189
They can throw it around.

02:14.800 --> 02:17.872
Benson, one of the reasons
we're not eating is because

02:18.080 --> 02:21.039
we are all worried and upset
about The Major's disappearance.

02:21.240 --> 02:24.711
And The Major would not
have disappeared if you
had been watching him.

02:24.920 --> 02:28.914
It ain't my job to watch him.
The less I see of him, the better.

02:29.160 --> 02:31.516
Benson, when was
the last time you saw him?

02:31.720 --> 02:32.756
I saw him this morning.

02:32.960 --> 02:35.520
He was running around
in that camouflage outfit of his,

02:35.720 --> 02:38.155
terrorising the gardener.

02:38.960 --> 02:39.960
Then he left.

02:40.160 --> 02:42.675
Did he say
where he was going, Benson?

02:42.920 --> 02:44.991
On patrol.

02:45.440 --> 02:47.113
Well, what does that mean?

02:47.320 --> 02:49.960
It means Grandpa's bonkers.

02:50.200 --> 02:53.830
It means, Jessica,
that he's gotten himself
into one hell of a fix again,

02:54.040 --> 02:55.474
that's what it means.

02:55.680 --> 02:58.514
It means, Jessica,
that in the course of 24 hours,

02:58.720 --> 03:02.316
your daughter has left home,
and your father has disappeared.

03:02.560 --> 03:06.156
It means that perhaps
you are letting this household
get the better of you.

03:06.400 --> 03:09.313
Oh, it's not her fault.
She's not responsible for the...

03:09.520 --> 03:11.398
Benson.

03:11.600 --> 03:13.398
You are sitting at the table.

03:15.320 --> 03:18.358
Good, Mr. Tate.

03:18.600 --> 03:21.354
And this is standing.

03:21.560 --> 03:24.837
And this is leaving.

03:26.680 --> 03:30.515
Jessica, do you remember
the last time your father
disappeared?

03:30.720 --> 03:35.272
Do you remember how
he took the 8:12 commuter train
into Manhattan

03:35.480 --> 03:38.712
and attacked
the German consulate?

03:38.960 --> 03:41.998
It caused
an international incident,
Jessica.

03:42.200 --> 03:45.398
I had to apologise
to two governments.

03:45.600 --> 03:47.080
And remember on December 7th,

03:47.280 --> 03:50.956
when he captured the entire staff
of Benihana's of Tokyo?

03:51.160 --> 03:52.833
[LAUGHING]

03:53.280 --> 03:57.240
It cost me a fortune
to keep him out of the
banana hatch that time, Jessica.

03:57.440 --> 03:59.079
At ease, men.
JESSICA: Oh, Daddy.

03:59.280 --> 04:01.920
There he is, Chester.
Where the devil have you been?

04:02.120 --> 04:03.156
Easy, colonel.

04:03.360 --> 04:07.718
I think your anger will be
assuaged when you see
what I have brought you.

04:07.920 --> 04:11.118
There he is.
One of the Nazi's
top spies.

04:11.320 --> 04:14.392
God, it's Mr. Kirby.
Oh, dear.

04:14.600 --> 04:17.637
Are you crazy?
This is Mr. Kirby,
our neighbour.

04:17.839 --> 04:20.798
Don't let him fool you.
He's a master of disguise.

04:21.000 --> 04:23.469
Mr. Kirby, I am...
I'm so sorry.

04:23.680 --> 04:26.639
Tate...
How about a nice glass
of iced tea, Mr. Kirby?

04:26.840 --> 04:28.797
I have had it, Tate.

04:29.000 --> 04:32.277
No, not a word.
Don't say a word. There is
nothing you can say to me, Tate.

04:32.480 --> 04:34.312
There is nothing
you can say to a man

04:34.520 --> 04:37.957
who has spent an
entire afternoon locked
in the trunk of his car.

04:38.160 --> 04:40.550
Oh. What man
was locked in the
trunk of his car?

04:40.760 --> 04:45.312
It isn't... It isn't enough
that I occasionally
get shot at.

04:45.520 --> 04:48.592
No, today... Today
I get into my car, and
halfway down the street

04:48.800 --> 04:51.156
a gun was placed
at the back of my head.

04:51.360 --> 04:52.840
I hid in the back seat.

04:53.040 --> 04:54.759
Some cold lemonade?

04:54.960 --> 04:55.996
I was then ord...

04:57.880 --> 05:00.679
I was then ordered
to drive out
to the city dump where...

05:00.880 --> 05:02.792
Where he proceeded
to grill me for hours

05:03.000 --> 05:04.878
about troop movements
on the Heifetz River.

05:05.120 --> 05:06.839
Yes, heh.
KIRBY:
I showed him my licence,

05:07.040 --> 05:10.112
My credit cards even,
to prove I was an American.

05:10.320 --> 05:12.994
I kept yelling out
of the trunk of the car,
"Corn Flakes,

05:13.200 --> 05:17.035
McDonald's,
Reggie Jackson,
toilet paper."

05:17.240 --> 05:20.233
I sang the
"Star-Spangled Banner,"
but he wouldn't believe me.

05:20.440 --> 05:21.874
Of course I didn't believe you.

05:22.080 --> 05:27.519
He couldn't tell me
who played third base
for the Yankees in 1931.

05:27.720 --> 05:28.870
Tell him, colonel.

05:32.200 --> 05:34.271
He doesn't know, you idiot.

05:34.760 --> 05:36.831
KIRBY:
So that's it, Tate.

05:37.040 --> 05:40.716
I'm going on record
right now, I swear,
if I ever catch that lunatic

05:40.920 --> 05:43.515
near me again,
I'll have him put away.

05:44.200 --> 05:46.760
JESSICA: A diet soda?
KIRBY: No.

05:47.720 --> 05:50.918
Will you try and understand?

05:51.120 --> 05:57.390
One more incident and
they are going to lock you up
and put you away.

05:58.040 --> 05:59.040
Yes, colonel.

06:00.640 --> 06:05.590
But once I'm on the inside,
I'll find out all their secrets,

06:05.800 --> 06:08.872
tunnel out,
and lead our boys
to safety.

06:09.080 --> 06:10.480
Good thinking, colonel.

06:10.680 --> 06:13.434
It's thinking like that
that's going to make you
a general

06:13.640 --> 06:15.836
before this war is over.

06:16.360 --> 06:18.317
[♪♪♪]

06:22.440 --> 06:24.033
Hey, hey.

06:24.240 --> 06:25.879
You. Yeah. Yeah, you.

06:26.080 --> 06:29.039
What is this,
some national holiday
I didn't hear about?

06:29.240 --> 06:31.072
I ought to start paying
you guys by the piece.

06:31.280 --> 06:33.192
Maybe I'll get
a little action
around here.

06:33.400 --> 06:35.480
Terrific. I ask
the union for some
high steel-workers.

06:35.600 --> 06:37.512
They send me
steel workers
who are high.

06:37.720 --> 06:39.154
Oh, you hippies.

06:39.360 --> 06:41.477
Burt.
Danny? Danny!

06:41.680 --> 06:45.469
Danny. Danny.
Danny,
what a surprise.

06:45.680 --> 06:48.957
Hey, good to see you, fella.

06:50.160 --> 06:52.675
Yeah, I know, I know.
Hard to find words,
isn't it, huh?

06:52.880 --> 06:54.758
Is that's some view,
huh? Look over there.

06:54.960 --> 06:57.156
Central Park.
Over there,
the World Trade Center.

06:57.360 --> 07:00.831
Down there, Fifth Avenue
from 42 storeys up. Huh?

07:01.040 --> 07:03.509
See all those little ants
down there?
Those are buses.

07:03.720 --> 07:05.234
Heh, heh, heh.

07:07.120 --> 07:08.120
Burt.
BURT:
What?

07:08.280 --> 07:09.475
Burt, listen.

07:09.680 --> 07:11.680
This friend of mine
has a cabin
up in the Poconos...

07:11.800 --> 07:13.920
Hey. You don't leave
that riveting gun there,
you jerk.

07:14.120 --> 07:16.555
What are you
trying to do?
Kill somebody?

07:16.760 --> 07:18.797
Last time somebody left
something like that
laying around, it fell.

07:19.000 --> 07:22.072
Knocked a hole
in a guy's head the size of
the Grand Canyon.

07:22.280 --> 07:24.670
Of course, the size
of the hole in his head
was relatively unimportant

07:24.880 --> 07:27.918
since he went
crashing down
700 feet anyway.

07:28.096 --> 07:30.976
You should've seen the thing.
What a mess.
I mean, picture a watermelon...

07:31.000 --> 07:33.834
Oh, Burt.
Sorry, Danny.
Go ahead, what is it?

07:34.200 --> 07:35.270
Burt, look.

07:35.480 --> 07:39.315
This friend of mine
has a cabin
up in the Poconos.

07:39.520 --> 07:41.830
I was wondering, maybe, uh...

07:42.040 --> 07:45.750
Maybe you'd like to go
up there fishing with me
tomorrow, huh?

07:45.960 --> 07:49.032
Hey, Danny. Danny. Danny.
Oh, Burt.

07:49.240 --> 07:52.392
Danny, you climbed
all the way up here to
ask me to go fishing with you?

07:52.600 --> 07:53.636
Oh, Danny.

07:53.840 --> 07:55.672
Danny, Danny,
you make me so happy.

07:55.880 --> 07:57.075
Am I happy.
Great.

07:57.280 --> 07:58.280
But I can't go.
What?

07:58.440 --> 07:59.794
Hey, you with the ponytail.

08:00.000 --> 08:01.801
Watch it,
you're gonna have no hair,
you creep.

08:01.960 --> 08:03.872
I mean, Chuck's
coming tonight
from Hawaii.

08:04.080 --> 08:05.992
I mean, can't we make it Saturday?
No, no, no.

08:06.200 --> 08:08.510
It's gotta be tomorrow.
Well, Danny, I'm sorry.

08:08.720 --> 08:09.880
I mean, I don't know how I...

08:10.080 --> 08:11.441
Look, Burt,
tomorrow's the only day

08:11.480 --> 08:12.630
that my friend will be away.

08:12.840 --> 08:15.878
Danny, I don't know...
Hey. Hey, you, Pocahontas,
over here.

08:16.080 --> 08:17.230
Put down the binoculars.

08:17.440 --> 08:19.238
This is for welding here,
not peeping.

08:19.440 --> 08:21.193
Burt, listen.

08:21.400 --> 08:24.438
You and me are going
fishing tomorrow
together, huh?

08:24.640 --> 08:27.633
In the Poconos,
you and me, fishing
together, tomorrow.

08:27.840 --> 08:28.840
Got it?

08:29.040 --> 08:31.350
Oh, Danny, I'm being
such an idiot.

08:31.560 --> 08:34.553
For the first time,
my stepson asks me
to do something with him,

08:34.760 --> 08:37.480
and here am I
trying to find reasons
why I can't. Hey.

08:37.679 --> 08:41.196
Danny. Well,
we're going fishing, and
we're going tomorrow, huh?

08:41.400 --> 08:43.789
I mean, after all,
I haven't seen Chuck
in 15 years.

08:44.000 --> 08:47.198
If I don't see him
for one day, it's not
going to kill me, is it?

08:47.400 --> 08:49.471
Hey, hey, you.
What are you, crazy up here?

08:49.680 --> 08:51.080
[SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

08:51.280 --> 08:53.158
DANNY:
Burt.
For Pete's sake.

08:53.360 --> 08:55.192
DANNY:
Burt.

08:56.840 --> 08:58.957
[♪♪♪]

08:59.160 --> 09:04.315
Eleven, 16, 21, carry the two.

09:05.600 --> 09:10.038
I cannot afford all this, Claire.
You are spending a fortune.

09:10.240 --> 09:12.038
Chester, you didn't
answer my question.

09:12.240 --> 09:14.357
I asked you if
you talked to Jessica.

09:14.560 --> 09:16.000
Well, of course I talked to Jessica.

09:16.160 --> 09:18.914
Every night when I go home,
I talk to Jessica.

09:19.120 --> 09:22.113
What's the matter with you, Claire?
Do I talk to Jessica?

09:22.320 --> 09:24.277
[CHUCKLING]

09:25.200 --> 09:28.079
Did you tell Jessica
that you're leaving her,
Chester?

09:28.280 --> 09:29.760
What is this?

09:29.960 --> 09:34.557
Two thousand dollars
for wallpaper for your apartment?

09:34.760 --> 09:37.639
Yes, Chester.
What are you papering the walls in?

09:37.840 --> 09:39.752
Currency?

09:40.000 --> 09:42.993
You know, Chester,
there is a solution to all this.

09:43.200 --> 09:45.954
If you leave Jessica
and move in with me,
I'll be happier.

09:46.160 --> 09:48.629
And when I'm happier,
I don't spend as much money.

09:48.840 --> 09:50.797
I'm sorry, Claire,
you'll just have to wait.

09:51.160 --> 09:53.516
Wait?
That's right, wait.

09:53.760 --> 09:56.514
Remember 10 years ago, Chester?

09:56.720 --> 09:59.120
Remember when you said
you couldn't leave
because little Billy

09:59.200 --> 10:01.396
had a perception problem,
and if you left then,

10:01.600 --> 10:04.434
then he might write backwards
for the rest of his life.

10:04.680 --> 10:06.034
So I waited.

10:06.280 --> 10:08.556
And then that cleared up,
and Billy could read

10:08.760 --> 10:11.798
but suddenly Eunice wouldn't
get out of her bathrobe
or leave her room

10:12.000 --> 10:13.878
and you couldn't leave then.

10:14.120 --> 10:15.156
So I waited.

10:15.680 --> 10:18.115
And then,
as soon as Eunice got dressed,

10:18.320 --> 10:20.960
Corinne stopped eating
and had to be hospitalised

10:21.160 --> 10:24.756
and you couldn't leave
until she was keeping solids down.

10:25.360 --> 10:27.397
And so I waited.

10:27.600 --> 10:30.195
Well, now Billy reads,
Eunice gets dressed,

10:30.400 --> 10:33.040
Corinne eats,
and I'm still waiting.

10:33.240 --> 10:34.799
Well, that's it for waiting,
Chester.

10:35.000 --> 10:38.038
You are going to leave Jessica now.
You are going to go home

10:38.240 --> 10:42.280
and tell her that you're leaving,
and if you don't, Chester, I will.

10:42.560 --> 10:43.560
[CHUCKLING]

10:43.720 --> 10:45.313
Fine. Go.

10:45.520 --> 10:48.592
I'll do it, Chester. I swear.

10:48.800 --> 10:49.800
Fine. Fine.

10:50.000 --> 10:51.957
Do you need directions to the house?

10:53.360 --> 10:56.558
I know where you live, Chester.
Good.

10:56.760 --> 11:00.151
Well, goodbye, Claire.

11:01.000 --> 11:03.037
Say hello to Jessica for me.

11:04.360 --> 11:05.714
[CHUCKLES]

11:06.040 --> 11:09.750
Go to my house and tell Jessica.
Heh, heh.

11:10.400 --> 11:13.711
Never try to bluff a bluffer.

11:13.920 --> 11:15.877
[♪♪♪]

11:19.160 --> 11:20.480
[♪♪♪]

11:20.680 --> 11:23.240
I'm so excited,
I can hardly
contain myself.

11:23.440 --> 11:25.716
After 15 years,
I'm gonna be
with my son.

11:26.280 --> 11:28.954
Another son.
Two sons in two weeks,
that's a son a week.

11:29.160 --> 11:30.594
I don't know.

11:30.800 --> 11:34.635
Oh, Mary, Mary, Mary,
I'm so excited. I haven't taken
a good breath all day.

11:34.840 --> 11:36.877
It's just excitement
because my son is coming.

11:37.080 --> 11:39.037
Either that or a heart attack.

11:39.240 --> 11:42.392
Yes. Oh, and
you guys. You guys
are gonna love him.

11:42.600 --> 11:44.273
I cant wait, Burt.

11:44.480 --> 11:48.360
I mean, I've always wanted to meet
a Hawaiian ventriloquist.

11:48.560 --> 11:49.630
Well, now you will.

11:51.560 --> 11:52.789
One of the best.

11:52.976 --> 11:54.616
He played all the big rooms
on the island.

11:54.640 --> 11:55.960
[DOORBELL RINGS]

11:56.160 --> 11:58.001
That's him. That's him.
Come on, up, he's here.

11:58.080 --> 11:59.594
Get up. There you go.

11:59.800 --> 12:01.757
[SINGING IN NORMAL
AND HIGH-PITCHED VOICES]

12:12.840 --> 12:14.069
Yeah.
Ha-ha.

12:14.280 --> 12:16.670
Chuck? Chuck.
CHUCK:
Hey, Dad.

12:16.880 --> 12:18.234
BURT:
Chuck.

12:19.720 --> 12:21.600
Did you see that?
Did you see it?
Isn't he great?

12:21.800 --> 12:23.678
Chuck, I'd like you
to meet my wife, Mary.

12:23.880 --> 12:26.839
And her two boys,
Danny and Jodie.
Hi.

12:27.040 --> 12:28.952
[IN HIGH-PITCHED VOICE]
Okay, I don't need
this. I'm leaving.

12:29.160 --> 12:30.514
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
Well, he didn't see you.

12:30.720 --> 12:33.997
I love that.
I didn't fly 6000 miles
to be stiffed.

12:34.200 --> 12:35.475
Isn't that cute? Cute.

12:36.760 --> 12:39.514
I really don't need
this aggravation from
the lower-middle class.

12:39.720 --> 12:41.393
Hey.

12:42.560 --> 12:46.713
Dad, could you say hi
to him? I think
his feelings are hurt.

12:50.080 --> 12:51.833
Well, sure.

12:52.400 --> 12:54.232
Hey, Bob.
Nice to see you again.

12:54.440 --> 12:56.716
Did you ever see
anything like that?

12:58.520 --> 13:00.239
Now apologise.

13:00.440 --> 13:02.318
Apologise?

13:02.520 --> 13:04.796
Well, for ignoring him.

13:07.080 --> 13:08.912
I am sorry. I
am really...

13:09.120 --> 13:12.431
Hey, Bob. Come on,
Bob. I'm sorry for
ignoring you like that.

13:12.640 --> 13:16.475
It's just that I was
so happy to see
Chuck here, you know?

13:20.280 --> 13:21.555
Uh, would you like a drink?

13:21.760 --> 13:24.753
Uh, no. Thanks.
Okay, then
I'll have one.

13:25.520 --> 13:28.877
Did anyone else notice
I wasn't introduced to
the rest of the family?

13:30.120 --> 13:31.713
What is it?
My skin's different?

13:31.920 --> 13:33.479
I'm not good enough?

13:34.720 --> 13:37.280
Oh, of course you are.

13:38.120 --> 13:40.077
Hi, Bob.

13:41.600 --> 13:43.637
I'm Mary.
Hi, Mary.

13:43.840 --> 13:45.433
And this is Danny.
How are you?

13:45.640 --> 13:47.597
Hi, Dan.
And that's Jodie.

13:47.800 --> 13:50.713
BOB:
Hello, Jodie.
Hi.

13:57.760 --> 14:01.959
And you get
uncomfortable around
homosexuals, huh?

14:02.200 --> 14:03.680
[SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

14:03.880 --> 14:06.520
Have an hors d'oeuvre.
I don't eat meat.

14:06.720 --> 14:08.518
Yuck.
I'm gonna
love it here.

14:08.720 --> 14:10.720
You know, this is
terrific. How do you
make it work?

14:10.880 --> 14:12.109
Get away from me!
Get away...

14:12.320 --> 14:14.437
Take it easy. Take it easy.
Take it easy?

14:14.640 --> 14:16.791
Well, did he look under
your clothes, huh?

14:17.000 --> 14:19.435
Can I look under her skirt?

14:23.480 --> 14:25.676
Bob's a little upset.
He hates to travel.

14:25.880 --> 14:27.712
Drop dead.

14:28.200 --> 14:29.270
Got a little plane sick.

14:29.480 --> 14:32.632
What did he do?
Throw up sawdust?

14:32.840 --> 14:34.672
[LAUGHING]

14:34.880 --> 14:37.520
Oh, fine. Now
the sissy's starting in.

14:37.720 --> 14:40.758
Hey, my brother
is not a sissy.
He's a...

14:40.960 --> 14:42.235
BOB:
Ahh!

14:43.040 --> 14:44.759
Bob. Bob.

14:44.960 --> 14:46.553
Bob, are you okay?
BOB:
Danny hurt me.

14:51.800 --> 14:54.190
What is it, Bob?
BOB:
My head is stuck.

14:56.160 --> 14:58.117
[GRUNTING]

14:58.720 --> 15:00.313
It's stuck.
BOB:
I know that. Help me!

15:00.520 --> 15:02.239
All right, all right.
I'm gonna do it.

15:04.120 --> 15:06.112
It's moving.
BOB:
Not that way.

15:08.680 --> 15:11.878
Hey, is he okay?

15:12.080 --> 15:13.275
He's fine.

15:13.480 --> 15:15.437
Knock on wood.

15:15.640 --> 15:17.597
[LAUGHING]

15:19.080 --> 15:21.549
Up your kazoo, butterfly.

15:21.760 --> 15:23.399
Hey...
Listen, uh,
would you like

15:23.600 --> 15:25.910
to freshen up
a little bit
before dinner?

15:26.120 --> 15:27.793
Yeah,
I'd like that.
Oh, well, good.

15:28.000 --> 15:31.277
You can just go right
upstairs and I'll bring up
your stuff in a minute or so.

15:31.480 --> 15:32.755
You can take a shower.

15:32.960 --> 15:36.351
All Bob needs
is a little
Lemon Pledge.

15:37.240 --> 15:39.835
I love Anita Bryant.

15:44.000 --> 15:45.957
I love your family.
Oh, this is great.

15:46.160 --> 15:49.073
Your father just
laughs and stutters,
the dame just sits,

15:49.280 --> 15:53.240
one guy's a fruit and
the other guy's got an
IQ slightly higher than kelp.

15:54.600 --> 15:56.478
Oh, it's great.

16:00.880 --> 16:03.270
Well, they had a long trip.

16:03.480 --> 16:05.711
I'm sure after
they get washed up
and rested,

16:05.920 --> 16:07.877
why, Bob will be
in a much better mood.

16:09.200 --> 16:10.759
Burt.

16:11.760 --> 16:13.433
He's a dummy.

16:13.680 --> 16:14.750
BOB:
I heard that!

16:14.960 --> 16:16.314
[MUTTERS]

16:16.520 --> 16:18.352
[♪♪♪]

16:18.560 --> 16:22.236
Believe me, Mrs. Tate,
I didn't want to be the one
to have to tell you this,

16:22.440 --> 16:26.150
but Chester just hasn't
given me any choice.
I'm sorry.

16:27.960 --> 16:29.314
[DOOR THUDS]

16:29.760 --> 16:31.877
Well, well, well,
look who's here.

16:32.080 --> 16:33.799
Glad to see you,
Mr. Tate.

16:34.000 --> 16:36.560
Nice to have you
home early. Let me
take that from you.

16:36.760 --> 16:39.400
All right, Benson,
you're being too nice.

16:39.600 --> 16:43.196
What's going on?
It's a surprise.

16:45.680 --> 16:47.319
Let me fix you a drink.

16:47.520 --> 16:50.274
Benson, how many times
do I have to tell you
I am on a diet?

16:50.480 --> 16:54.269
I don't want a drink.
You're gonna want this one.

16:55.160 --> 16:56.958
I said, no.

16:57.160 --> 16:59.231
Where is Mrs. Tate?
In the dining room.

16:59.440 --> 17:03.150
Why don't you pop in
and say hello?

17:07.319 --> 17:09.039
[MUTTERING]

17:09.760 --> 17:12.150
Hello, Chester.
I was just leaving.

17:12.359 --> 17:13.999
Well, nice seeing you,
Mrs. Tate.

17:14.200 --> 17:18.194
I'm sorry it couldn't
have been under more
pleasant circumstances.

17:24.800 --> 17:25.950
Jessica...
Chester, I...

17:26.160 --> 17:28.071
I know, horrified.
I... I...

17:28.280 --> 17:29.316
Speechless.

17:29.520 --> 17:32.957
I'm speechless,
Chester, and anguished.

17:33.160 --> 17:38.918
I know, I know.
I'm, uh, anguished
and speechless.

17:39.120 --> 17:41.635
I wish there were
something I could say.

17:41.840 --> 17:44.309
Well, there's nothing to say, Chester.
Oh, well, of course.

17:44.520 --> 17:48.639
I mean, of course words
can't express the, uh...
The sorrow.

17:48.840 --> 17:50.638
The tragedy.

17:50.840 --> 17:51.910
Tragedy?

17:52.120 --> 17:55.670
Well, maybe tragedy.
Okay, I guess tragedy.

17:55.920 --> 17:58.515
And horror.
Oh, horror, yes.

17:58.720 --> 18:00.552
The horror...

18:07.960 --> 18:10.077
I'm sorry, Jess. I'm...

18:10.280 --> 18:13.398
From the bottom of my heart,
I'm sorry you had to hear.

18:13.600 --> 18:17.071
Please, don't apologise, Chester.
Oh, well, I know it's just words...

18:17.280 --> 18:19.033
You must promise me
one thing, Chester.

18:19.240 --> 18:20.640
I'll get rid of her, Jess.

18:20.840 --> 18:22.752
You must promise me
not to fire her.

18:22.960 --> 18:24.394
Absol...

18:25.240 --> 18:26.276
What?

18:26.760 --> 18:29.320
Well, Chester,
I mean that girl is sick.

18:29.520 --> 18:33.036
She is so far gone already
that something like that

18:33.240 --> 18:36.472
might just push her
right over the edge.

18:42.320 --> 18:46.872
Yes, I... I see
what you mean. Yes.

18:47.840 --> 18:50.355
JESSICA:
Oh, poor, sad girl.

18:50.560 --> 18:54.952
I mean, Chester,
to be so much
in love with you

18:55.160 --> 18:58.631
that she's convinced
herself that you feel
the same way.

19:03.800 --> 19:05.519
And, Chester, that's not all.

19:05.720 --> 19:06.720
I mean, to believe...

19:06.880 --> 19:09.918
And believe me,
Chester, I mean, she
really does believe it,

19:10.120 --> 19:14.194
that you're actually
having an affair
with her.

19:15.640 --> 19:17.154
The mind, Jess.

19:17.360 --> 19:20.034
The tricks the mind plays.

19:20.240 --> 19:22.960
Poor thing.
Yes.

19:28.280 --> 19:31.193
Well, Chester,
you know, under
the circumstances,

19:31.400 --> 19:33.995
I mean, it's not
really her fault.

19:34.200 --> 19:37.910
I mean, what woman
in the world wouldn't fall
in love with you, Chester?

19:39.160 --> 19:41.550
Oh, I don't know.

19:45.880 --> 19:51.114
Now, I'm going to
go upstairs and
draw a nice, hot bath.

19:51.320 --> 19:55.872
So you can have
a good, long, relaxing
soak before dinner.

19:56.080 --> 19:57.309
Okay?

20:00.480 --> 20:02.836
Benson, why are you
standing there
with that martini?

20:03.040 --> 20:04.633
I told you I was on the diet.

20:04.840 --> 20:10.154
Mr. Tate, I have seen
dumb luck in my time.

20:10.360 --> 20:15.879
I have seen a guy fill an inside
straight flush to beat four aces.

20:16.080 --> 20:20.393
I have seen a guy hit
the daily double
for two solid weeks.

20:20.600 --> 20:21.716
Straight.

20:21.920 --> 20:28.190
But I have never, at no time,
seen nothing like this.

20:28.400 --> 20:30.357
[♪♪♪]

20:35.280 --> 20:37.476
BURT:
Danny, you should've seen
the look on your face.

20:37.680 --> 20:40.115
Well, I thought it was a snake.
A snake with leaves?

20:40.320 --> 20:42.915
Hey, you know, Danny,
I'm so happy.

20:43.120 --> 20:46.397
Yeah. Me too.
I mean, to have a real buddy.

20:46.600 --> 20:49.115
I mean... You know,
I've always been
kind of a loner.

20:49.320 --> 20:53.109
I don't have a lot of friends,
so to have a buddy who
lives in the same house...

20:53.320 --> 20:56.597
And now Peter's here.
And Chuck and Bob
are here.

20:56.800 --> 20:58.632
Well, I guess it's not fair
to count Bob.

20:58.840 --> 21:00.832
He's a... you know,
one of those.

21:01.040 --> 21:02.480
Hey, what are you doing?
Don't clean.

21:02.520 --> 21:04.512
I got to.
This place
is a mess.

21:04.720 --> 21:05.836
Yeah, leave it, leave it.

21:06.040 --> 21:08.635
Your mother's not here,
we can feel free to be slobs.

21:08.840 --> 21:11.036
Oh, your mother.
Oh, is she happy.

21:11.240 --> 21:13.391
Did you see her face
when we left this morning?

21:13.600 --> 21:17.230
There with those
great, big, glistening eyes
and that little smile of hers.

21:17.440 --> 21:19.875
You know, the one
when she doesn't
open her lips.

21:20.080 --> 21:22.276
That's her most very,
very, very pleased smile.

21:22.480 --> 21:24.631
The big smile is
her moderately pleased smile.

21:24.840 --> 21:27.196
That little smile,
where she doesn't
smile at all,

21:27.400 --> 21:30.871
that is, oddly enough, her most
happy smile. And that was the smile
she was smiling this morning.

21:31.080 --> 21:33.160
Danny, what are you doing?
Let's get out on the lake.

21:33.320 --> 21:35.676
I gotta get this stuff out of the way.
Why?

21:35.880 --> 21:36.916
Well, uh...

21:37.120 --> 21:40.113
Well, how are we gonna cook fish
if we can't get to the fireplace?

21:40.320 --> 21:41.674
On the stove.

21:42.120 --> 21:45.318
Burt, fish you buy in the store,
you cook on a stove.

21:45.520 --> 21:49.196
Fish you catch,
you cook in a fireplace.

21:51.200 --> 21:52.350
There's nothing here.

21:52.600 --> 21:56.116
Yeah. Well, I mean, ashes,
but, Danny, that' s normal
for a fireplace.

21:56.320 --> 21:57.436
Funny guy.

21:57.640 --> 22:00.600
Funny guy. Come on, Dan.
Let's get out on the lake,
see how they're hitting.

22:00.800 --> 22:03.634
Tonight we get a fish fry for...

22:06.760 --> 22:08.399
Uh, Danny?

22:08.800 --> 22:10.996
Uh, Danny, where are you, Danny?

22:11.200 --> 22:13.317
DANNY:
I'm... I'm up here.

22:14.920 --> 22:17.276
Danny, uh,
what are you doing
up the chimney?

22:17.480 --> 22:19.039
Cleaning out the flue.

22:20.640 --> 22:21.994
Cleaning out the flue?

22:22.200 --> 22:23.634
Funny guy.
Walks into a cabin,

22:23.840 --> 22:26.400
goes right up the chimney,
cleans out a flue.

22:26.600 --> 22:28.600
Eh, that could be
a safety precaution.
I don't know.

22:28.720 --> 22:29.720
[THUD]

22:29.880 --> 22:31.280
DANNY: Hey, don't touch that.
BURT: What is it?

22:31.480 --> 22:33.790
DANNY: Nothing. Just leave it alone.
It just fell down the chimney.

22:34.000 --> 22:35.639
I know it fell.
Yeah, what's in it?

22:35.840 --> 22:38.480
Nothing. I need it,
though. Give it to me,
Burt.

22:38.680 --> 22:40.797
I found it.
All right. All right, all right.

22:41.680 --> 22:44.036
From the looks of this place,
it's probably garbage.

22:44.240 --> 22:45.640
Funny, you think
you know somebody.

22:45.840 --> 22:48.753
At home, your room's
a mess, you throw food
all over the kitchen.

22:48.960 --> 22:52.078
We go away for the
weekend, you turn out
to be Louis Pasteur.

22:52.280 --> 22:54.920
Hey, Danny,
you're full of surprises.

22:57.440 --> 23:01.116
Uh, Danny, that's a gun.
Put it down,
that's dangerous.

23:03.240 --> 23:05.709
Uh, Danny,
what are you doing?
You're pointing a gun at me.

23:05.920 --> 23:07.195
I'm gonna kill you, Burt.

23:07.400 --> 23:08.470
Pfft. Heh-heh.

23:08.680 --> 23:10.797
That's funny. Oh.

23:12.080 --> 23:14.037
[♪♪♪]

23:17.360 --> 23:18.360
[♪♪♪]

